<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-213-736  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 213 736.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Feb 27 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Canada: marijuana virus strikes Parliament Hill. (computer virusattacks)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Buckler, Grant.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer virusesMicrocomputersCanada. Parliament. House of CommonsLegal IssuesToronto, University of.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>CANADA: MARIJUANA VIRUS STRIKES PARLIAMENT HILL OTTAWA, ONTARIO, CANADA, 1990FEB 16 (NB) -- A computer virus that urges legalization of marijuana hastaken its message to Canada's lawmakers, cropping up on 34 personal computersin the federal bureaucracy.andM;Jim Watson, director of communications for the office of the Speaker of theCanadian House of Commons, told Newsbytes the virus surfaced on a handful ofPCs, prompting a check of machines throughout Commons offices.andP;  Of 750machines, the relatively harmless virus was found on 34, Watson said.andP;  Nonewere in the offices of members of parliament, he added.andM;Meanwhile the University of Toronto, one of at least two Toronto sites hit bythe virus recently, expects to be stuck with the problem for a while.andO;Professor Will Cluett of the university's chemical engineering departmenttold Newsbytes that with open access to his department's microcomputer lab,stamping out the virus is almost impossible.andP;  &quot;The virus doesn't seem to bedoing anything too destructive,&quot; he said, so users will just have to livewith its occasional interruptions -- at least until summer vacation, whenthere may be time for a thorough disinfecting job.andM;The marijuana virus flashes on a PC's screen the message: &quot;Your computer isnow stoned.andP;  Legalize marijuana.&quot; Unlike more vicious viruses, however, itdoes not delete or garble files on the computer's hard disk.andM;(Grant Buckler/19900222/Press Contact: Jim Watson, House of Commons Speaker'sOffice, 613-992-5042; Will Cluett, University of Toronto, 416-978-6697)</TEXT></DOC>